03837nam a22005055i 9780887553394DE-B159720240306125748.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20072011xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97808875533947 a10.1515/97808875533942doi  a(DE-B1597)664679  a(OCoLC)1408681238  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxcCA 7aSOC0210002bisacsh1 aMcKegney, Sam, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aMagic Weapons :bAboriginal Writers Remaking Community after Residential School /cSam McKegney. 1aWinnipeg, Manitoba : bUniversity of Manitoba Press, c[2007] 4c©2011  a1 online resource (241 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tForeword -- tAcknowledgements and Permissions -- tIntroduction -- tAcculturation through Education -- tReading Residential School -- t“We have been silent too long” -- t“Analyze, if you wish, but listen” -- tFrom Trickster Poetics to Transgressive Politics -- tCreative Interventions in the Residential School Legacy -- tEndnotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe legacy of the residential school system ripples throughout Native Canada, its fingerprints on the domestic violence, poverty, alcoholism, drug abuse, and suicide rates that continue to cripple many Native communities. Magic Weapons is the first major survey of Indigenous writings on the residential school system, and provides groundbreaking readings of life writings by Rita Joe (Mi’kmaq) and Anthony Apakark Thrasher (Inuit) as well as in-depth critical studies of better known life writings by Basil Johnston (Ojibway) and Tomson Highway (Cree). Magic Weapons examines the ways in which Indigenous survivors of residential school mobilize narrative in their struggles for personal and communal empowerment in the shadow of attempted cultural genocide. By treating Indigenous life-writings as carefully crafted aesthetic creations and interrogating their relationship to more overtly politicized historical discourses, Sam McKegney argues that Indigenous life-writings are culturally generative in ways that go beyond disclosure and recompense, re-envisioning what it means to live and write as Indigenous individuals in post-residential school Canada.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Ethnic Studies / Native American Studies.2bisacsh1 aJohnston, Basil H., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJohnston, Basil, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package 2011-2010z978311127414008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2011 - 2010z978311127721940uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978088755339440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780887553394423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780887553394/original  a978-3-11-127414-0  ACUP Complete eBook-Package 2011-2010c2010d2011  a978-3-11-127721-9  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2011 - 2010c2010d2011  aGBV-deGruyter-alles